Kenwan Cheung - Machine Learning - Final Project¶

Catnet - Detecting images of cats - classification project.¶

Goal:

The goal of this project is to reapproach one of the original kaggle datasets - Dogs vs Cats image classification.

Early discussion:

Image classification has become a very interesting application space with the rise of convolutional neural nets. That being said, I wanted to take the opportunity to both apply CNNs as well as compare their results vs that of other ML methods.

However, I wanted to tackle this problem set knowing that I have a limited max of computing power due to having a mobile laptop as well as having no GPUs to speed up the process.

Thus for our CNN in particular, we had to undergo some data augmentation.

Methodology:

We will attempt to classify the images with a variety of approaches:

  1. K-Nearest Neighbors
  2. Tree based approaches (RF / GBT)
  3. SVMs
  4. A CNN approach

Evaluation:

We'll use the standard evaluation techniques across models. ROC curves (true vs false positive), AUC values, accuracy and sensitivity etc...

Summary:

In the end, the tree based models performed very well on a histogram of pixel intensity. The lack of a large training set meant that some promising validation test values of 80%+ did not translate into our test set outside of the validation results.

That being said, we can see the promise in the CNN application. We did not do much fine tuning, nor go to the depth that we could.

The CNN technology we're using is from 2014, which is an eternity in the field of deep learning. Current innovations have included ever deeper networks, different activation functions that are asymptotic to 0 rather than ReLu (0,max), as well as residual neural networks where we incorporate fits on weights to the residuals rather purely on the original mapping.

Despite this project, there is much much more to learn!

In [4]:
# color hist
def extract_color_histogram(image, bins=(8,8,8)):
    hsv = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
    hist = cv2.calcHist([hsv],[0,1,2], None, bins,
                       [0,180,0,256,0,256])
    if imutils.is_cv2():
        hist = cv2.normalize(hist)
    else:
        cv2.normalize(hist,hist)
    return hist.flatten()

In [5]:
def read_image(file_path):
    img = cv2.imread(file_path, cv2.IMREAD_COLOR) #cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE
    return cv2.resize(img, (ROWS, COLS))#, interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)

def prep_data(images):
    count = len(images)
    data = np.ndarray((count, CHANNELS, ROWS, COLS), dtype=np.uint8)

    for i, image_file in enumerate(images):
        image = read_image(image_file)
        data[i] = image.T
        if i%250 == 0: print('Processed {} of {}'.format(i, count))
    
    return data

In [359]:
# let's grid search across our range of values
neighbors = 2
cv_scores = []

for k in range(1,neighbors):
    print("[INFO] Fitting with {} Neighbors".format(k))
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    print(start)
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=neighbors,
                             n_jobs=-1)
    scores = cross_val_score(knn, features_train, labels_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
    print("[INFO] histogram accuracy {}%".format(cv_scores))
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    print(end)
    tdelta = end - start
    print("[INFO] time duration {}".format(divmod(tdelta.total_seconds(), 60)))

In [444]:
scores = ['precision', 'recall']

for score in scores:
    print("# Tuning hyper-parameters for %s" % score)
    print()

    svm_cv = GridSearchCV(svm.SVC(), tuned_parameters, cv=5,
                       scoring='%s_macro' % score)
    svm_cv.fit(features_train, labels_train)

    print("Best parameters set found on development set:")
    print()
    print(svm_cv.best_params_)
    print()
    print("Grid scores on development set:")
    print()
    means = svm_cv.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
    stds = svm_cv.cv_results_['std_test_score']
    for mean, std, params in zip(means, stds, svm_cv.cv_results_['params']):
        print("%0.3f (+/-%0.03f) for %r"
              % (mean, std * 2, params))
    print()

    print("Detailed classification report:")
    print()
    print("The model is trained on the full development set.")
    print("The scores are computed on the full evaluation set.")
    print()
    y_true, y_pred = labels_test, svm_cv.predict(features_test)
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))
    print()

Data augmentation comments¶

We can see what the augmentation generator is doing. It will stretch, flip, rotate, etc...

This allows us to artificially increase the size of our small dataset (for a NN).

Some general comments on NN¶

Neural nets take a lot of computing power to train. I do not have those capabilities. As such I am a little constrained with data, which impacts the effectiveness as a method. Still, some valuable learnigns are generate.

The ideal would be to have a deep and long running network, but based on the limitations of my laptop, that might not be feasible.

A deeper but less iterated network also has some issues with overfits as well.

Additional comments about steps below:¶

I've tried many different iterations (essentially manual grid searching) as best as I can. Only some of them are listed below.

Depth, width, # of runs, normalization vs not... These combinations are the things tackled below

In [357]:
# Define loss history

## Callback for loss logging per epoch
class LossHistory(Callback):
    def on_train_begin(self, logs={}):
        self.losses = []
        self.val_losses = []
        
    def on_epoch_end(self, batch, logs={}):
        self.losses.append(logs.get('loss'))
        self.val_losses.append(logs.get('val_loss'))

def dognet():
    
    model = Sequential()

    # original below
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=(3, 150, 150)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Flatten())  # this converts our 3D feature maps to 1D feature vectors
    model.add(Dense(64))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model


model = dognet()
In [249]:
def run_dognet():
    history = LossHistory()
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    print("[INFO] Starting NN fit on {}".format(start))

    model.fit_generator(
        train_generator,
        steps_per_epoch=2000 // batch_size,
        epochs=50,
        verbose=1,
        validation_data=validation_generator,
        validation_steps=800 // batch_size)
    
    predictions = model.predict_generator(test_generator,800/batch_size,verbose=1)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    print("[INFO] Finished fit on {}".format(end))
    
    tdelta = end-start
    print("[INFO] time duration {}".format(divmod(tdelta.total_seconds(), 60)))
    
    return predictions, history

predictions, history = run_dognet()

# 50 epochs, deeper
def dognet_deeper():
    
    model = Sequential()

    # original below
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=(3, 150, 150)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

#     model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
#     model.add(Activation('relu'))
#     model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Flatten())  # this converts our 3D feature maps to 1D feature vectors
    model.add(Dense(128))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model


model_deeper = dognet_deeper()

# set lambda parameter
l2_lambda = 0.001

# 50 epochs, deeper, regularization
def dognet_deeper_reg():
    
    model = Sequential()

    # original below
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=(3, 150, 150),kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3),kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())    
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3),kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3),kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3),kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Flatten())  # this converts our 3D feature maps to 1D feature vectors
    model.add(Dense(128))
#     model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(1))
#     model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

model_deeper_reg = dognet_deeper_reg()

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

#     model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
#     model.add(Activation('relu'))
#     model.add(MaxPooling2D(data_format="channels_first", pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Flatten())  # this converts our 3D feature maps to 1D feature vectors
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))

    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))

    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model


model_deeper2 = dognet_deeper2()

def run_dognet():
    history = LossHistory()
    start = datetime.datetime.now()
    print("[INFO] Starting NN fit on {}".format(start))

    model_deeper2.fit_generator(
        train_generator,
        steps_per_epoch=2000 // batch_size,
        epochs=5,
#         callbacks=[early_stopping],    
        verbose=1,
        validation_data=validation_generator,
        validation_steps=800 // batch_size)
    
    predictions = model_deeper2.predict_generator(test_generator,800/batch_size,verbose=1)
    end = datetime.datetime.now()
    print("[INFO] Finished fit on {}".format(end))
    
    tdelta = end-start
    print("[INFO] time duration {}".format(divmod(tdelta.total_seconds(), 60)))
    
    return predictions, history

SUMMARY OF NN RESULTS¶

We can see that there are some issues with our small data set with limited image size.

There are three main issues:

  • Deeper is not ALWAYS better. In this case, we don't have the fidelity of images or the sample size to pick up the variety of signals that lead to superb accuracy.

  • Regularization had no impact on the simple model with only 3 layers, but had a pretty detrimental impact on the deep model with regularization.

  • All in all, we still have not matched in the out of sample results of the randomforest, which also has the added benefit of fitting quicker and predicting quicker.

Some additional thoughts¶

An ideal next step with a lack of computational power would be to use pre-loaded weights of a state of the art model. While I don't do that there, we should expect to see accuracies ~95+%.

Summary across results.¶

We can see that both tree based models did pretty well with high AUC scores and good ROC curve tradeoffs. We would probably settle on the tree based approach of GBT in the end.

Our NN were pretty weak out of the test set. We clearly need to increase the size of our training data to really get good accuracy.

This has the added impact as well of preventing us from going too deep in depth, as evidenced by the negative correlation.

I want to try one last approach, and that's ensembling our predictions.

Comments on ensemble¶
